# =============================================================================
# Vercel (Production)
# =============================================================================
# API keys are NOT read from this file on Vercel. Add them in the dashboard so
# they inject at build time:
#
#   Vercel → your project → Settings → Environment Variables
#   - Add each REACT_APP_* you use (names must match exactly).
#   - Environment: Production (and Preview if you want previews to work).
#   - Redeploy after saving (Deployments → … → Redeploy), or push a new commit.
#
# Browser-visible keys use the REACT_APP_ prefix (embedded in the JS bundle).
# =============================================================================

# --- Steam Web API (Store catalog: names, images, descriptions, Metacritic) ---
# Create a key: https://steamcommunity.com/dev/apikey
#
# This app (Create React App) embeds only REACT_APP_* at build time. Use REACT_APP_STEAM_WEB_API_KEY
# on Vercel Production — a plain STEAM_API_KEY will not appear in the browser bundle.
# Optional aliases (same value; first non-empty wins): NEXT_PUBLIC_STEAM_API_KEY, STEAM_API_KEY.
REACT_APP_STEAM_WEB_API_KEY=your_steam_web_api_key_here
# NEXT_PUBLIC_STEAM_API_KEY=your_steam_web_api_key_here
# STEAM_API_KEY=your_steam_web_api_key_here
#
# Vercel / production browser: npm start proxies /api/steam-store → store.steampowered.com (see setupProxy.js).
# This repo’s vercel.json adds the same proxy on Vercel. Set this so production hits your rewrite (avoids CORS):
#   REACT_APP_STEAM_STORE_PROXY=/api/steam-store
